    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-07-27T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-07-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="277"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d277">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8993: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-07-27T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 27, 1937—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>320. Your 505, July 27, 1 p.m. Department is telegraphing Peiping and Tokyo<note
                        n="86" xml:id="d277fn86">See telegram No. 128, July 27, 1 p.m, <ref
                            target="frus1937v04#pg_238">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p.
                            238</ref>.</note> instructing our Embassies there to confer immediately
                    with the British Embassies and in their discretion to take action on lines
                    parallel with the British action toward dissuading the Japanese authorities from
                    proceeding with any plan for military operations which would be likely to
                    endanger the lives of American nationals.</p>
                <p>Please inform the Foreign Office.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
